# Day 2 – Arrays

Today I started learning about arrays, which are one of the most important topics in DSA. Since Python uses lists as arrays, I practiced basic operations like accessing, updating, inserting, and removing elements. I also learned which operations are fast and which become slower because of shifting elements.

## What I Practiced

### Accessing Elements

```python
num = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25]

print(num[0])
print(num[2])
print(num[-1])
```

### Updating an Element

```python
num = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25]

num.pop(1)
num.insert(1, 100)

print(num)
```

> 💡 Later I learned that this can also be done more efficiently with:
>
> ```python
> num[1] = 100
> ```

### Appending an Element

```python
num = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25]

num.append(30)

print(num)
```

### Removing the Last Element

```python
num = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25]

num.pop()

print(num)
```

### Challenge – Find the Largest Element

```python
arr = [18, 4, 72, 31, 9, 55]
max=arr[0]
for i in range(len(arr)-1):
    if max<=arr[i]:
        max=arr[i]
print(max)
```
